### Crates in Rust

A crate is Rust's compilation unit. It can be a binary (executable) or a library. Crates are the foundation of code distribution and reuse.

---

### Crate Types

| Type | Entry Point | Purpose |
|------|-------------|---------|
| Binary crate | `src/main.rs` | Produces an executable |
| Library crate | `src/lib.rs` | Produces a reusable library |

---

### Working with Crates

```rust
// Using external crates (in Cargo.toml)
// [dependencies]
// serde = { version = "1.0", features = ["derive"] }
// rand = "0.8"

// In source code
use serde::{Serialize, Deserialize};
use rand::Rng;

// Your crate as a library
pub fn add(x: i32, y: i32) -> i32 {
    x + y
}

// Multiple crates in a workspace
// [workspace]
// members = ["crate_a", "crate_b"]
```

### Crate Structure

```
my_crate/
  Cargo.toml
  src/
    main.rs    (or lib.rs for library)
    submodule.rs
  tests/
    integration_test.rs
  examples/
    example.rs
```

> **Key Point:** Library crates are reusable across projects. Binary crates are executables. A package can contain one library crate and multiple binary crates. Crates are published to crates.io for public distribution.

codeExample:
// In src/lib.rs - library crate
pub mod math {
    pub fn add(a: i32, b: i32) -> i32 { a + b }
    pub fn multiply(a: i32, b: i32) -> i32 { a * b }
}

pub fn greet(name: &str) -> String {
    format!("Hello, {}!", name)
}

// Using in another project:
// use my_crate::{math, greet};
